name: 3-sulfolene
Reason: 3-sulfolene has a melting point influenced by its structural components. Starting with the basic unit of benzene, which has a melting point of 5.5 °C, we have substantial structural components to consider. 3-sulfolene has two fused aromatic rings, which typically increase the melting point due to increased molecular rigidity and pi-stacking interactions; this effect is estimated to add about +25 °C for each additional fused ring. The molecular structure also includes a sulfur atom, which can participate in hydrogen bonding and rigidify the structure, estimated at around +10 °C.
